The IoT is a system that connects different devices in order to share information and interact with each other. Gartner forecasts that there will be 20 billion connected objects by 2020. Gartner sees many opportunities for enterprises, such as improved productivity, energy management and health care delivery. Further potential applications include home security systems, transportation, retail store checkouts, smart grid distribution networks, smart building control systems and intelligent street lighting network management. Gartner sees many challenges for enterprises, such as privacy issues, technology obsolescence and competition from startups and established companies outside their existing supply chain ecosystems. Gartner warns against thinking it is just another name for machine-to-machine communication or smart grid technology. Gartner sees many possible risks associated with the evolution of the internet beyond human access including environmental damage due to greenhouse gas emission, loss of personal identity or loss of privacy due to data collection on individuals or loss of individual freedom due to loss of independence from digital dependency.
